# Power Consumption Standards (Embedded)

This document defines power management standards for battery-powered and energy-constrained embedded systems: sleep modes, peripheral gating, wake sources, and duty cycling.

---

## Core Principle: Default to Lowest Power State

The system should spend the maximum possible time in the deepest sleep mode. Every peripheral, clock domain, and voltage rail that is not actively needed must be disabled.

---

## Sleep Mode Hierarchy

### Mode Definitions

| Mode | CPU | SRAM | Peripherals | Wake Latency | Typical Current |
|------|-----|------|-------------|--------------|-----------------|
| Active | Running | Retained | Enabled | N/A | 10-50 mA |
| Sleep (WFI) | Halted | Retained | Enabled | < 1 us | 2-10 mA |
| Stop / Low-power sleep | Halted | Retained | Gated | 2-10 us | 10-100 uA |
| Standby / Deep sleep | Off | Partial | Off | 100 us - 5 ms | 1-10 uA |
| Shutdown / Off | Off | Lost | Off | Full boot | < 1 uA |

### Mode Selection Rules

| Condition | Recommended Mode | Rationale |
|-----------|-----------------|-----------|
| Idle between periodic tasks (< 10 ms) | Sleep (WFI) | Fast wake, low overhead |
| No work for 10 ms - 1 s | Stop mode | Significant power savings |
| No work for > 1 s | Standby | Deep savings, SRAM may be lost |
| Shipping / storage | Shutdown | Minimal battery drain |

